    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mothers Can't Win</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gloria DiPietro Cooper letter disputes Lisa Belkin's April 5 article on motherhood, which focused on increasing number of birth mothers giving up children for adoption and described case of Gina Bruystens (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Let's see -- one adoption agency received $12,500; a second, $6,000; the adoptive parents got the child of their dreams. And Gina Bruystens, struggling to pay her bills, received $400 a month, had some medical bills paid during her pregnancy and got a box of new maternity clothes. Oh, I almost forgot. Her son got a stuffed animal.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Let's see -- one adoption agency received $12,500; a second, $6,000; the adoptive parents got the child of their dreams. And Gina Bruystens, struggling to pay her bills, received $400 a month, had some medical bills paid during her pregnancy and got a box of new maternity clothes. Oh, I almost forgot. Her son got a stuffed animal.</p>
        <p>Perhaps I missed something in Belkin's article -- a current definition of ''control,'' perhaps?</p>
        <p>Gloria Di Pietro Cooper  Southbury, Conn.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
